{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἐκκαίω</b>, <br /> <i>Attic dialect</i> <b>ἐκκάω</b>, <i>future</i> -καύσω: <i>aorist</i> I ἐξέκαυσα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.134 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], but <i>participle</i> ἐκκέαντες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Rhesus” 97 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>burn out,</b> τοὺς ὀφθαλμούς τινος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.18; τὸ φῶς Κύκλωπος 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Cyclops” 633, compare 657 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, ἐκκάεσθαι τοὺς ὀφθαλμούς <b>to have one's eyes burnt out,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 473c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>light up, kindle,</b> τὰ πυρά [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.134, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Rh.” [prev. cited]; ἐκκέας τῶν ξύλων ἅττ᾽ ἂν ᾖ δανότατα 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 1133 (Lyric poetry): _metaphorically_, ἐ. πόλεμον, ἐλπίδα, 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 3.3.3, 5.108.5; τοὺς θυμούς 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 7.35; τὴν πρὸς αὐτὸν ὀργήν 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Fabius Maximus” 7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>provoke</b> to anger, ἔκ με κάεις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Herodas Mimographus 4.49 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; <b>inflame</b> with curiosity, <b>excite,</b> τινά [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Alex.” 30; ἴσῃ φιλοτιμίᾳ πρός τε τὸν δῆμον ἑαυτοὺς καὶ τὸν δῆμον πρὸς ἑαυτοὺς ἐκκαύσαντες 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Agis” 2 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <b>to be kindled, burn up,</b> τὸ πῦρ ἐκκάεται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Eupolis Comicus 340; ἐ. τὸ κακόν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 556a; ὀργὴν ἐκκαῆναι LXX.2Ki